'''Hollister Ridge''' is a group of [[seamount]]s in the [[Pacific Ocean]]. They lie west from the [[Pacific-Antarctic Ridge]] and form three [[Ridge|ridges]] that form a line; one of the ridges rises to a depth of {{convert|100|m}} and in the past formed an island. The seamounts are composed out of [[Basalt|basaltic]] and other rocks and their ages range from about 2.5 million years ago to latest [[Pleistocene]]; an acoustic swarm recorded in the southern [[Pacific Ocean]] in 1991-1992 is considered to be the manifestation of a historical eruption of the Hollister Ridge.

The origin of the Hollister Ridge is unclear, with various proposed mechanisms involving the neighbouring Pacific-Antarctic Ridge, [[crust (geology)|crust]]al weaknesses and the [[Louisville hotspot]].

== History ==

The ridge was discovered either by [[gravimetry]] from [[satellite]]s{{sfn|Vlastelic|Dosso|Guillou|Bougault|1998|p=777}} or by the research ship ''[[USNS Eltanin (T-AK-270)|Eltanin]]''{{sfn|Castillo|Natland|Niu|Lonsdale|1998|p=111}} in 1965 and first named "Hollister Ridge" in a 1995 publication.{{sfn|Okal|Langenhorst|2000|p=185}} [[Sample (material)|Rock samples]] were taken at the ridge in 1996.{{sfn|Vlastelic|Dosso|Guillou|Bougault|1998|p=777}}

== Geography and geomorphology ==

The Hollister Ridge is an [[aseismic ridge]] in the [[Pacific Ocean]], wesof the [[Pacific-Antarctic Ridge]].{{sfn|Vlastelic|Dosso|Guillou|Bougault|1998|p=777}} It consists of three separate ridges which are lined up in east-southeast to north-northwest direction, starting from the axis of the Pacific-Antarctic Ridge and ending in the direction of the [[Louisville seamount chain]]. The eastern ridge is {{convert|70|km}} long and rises to a depth of {{convert|1400|m}} below sea level, the central ridge is {{convert|207|km}} long and rises to a depth of {{convert|100|m}} below sea level, the western ridge is {{convert|50|km}} long and rises to a depth of {{convert|1500|m}} below sea level.{{sfn|Vlastelic|Dosso|Guillou|Bougault|1998|p=778,779}} The central ridge formed an island in the past.{{sfn|Vlastelic|Dosso|Guillou|Bougault|1998|p=779}}

== Geology ==

The ridge rises from a seafloor whose age decreases from 7-8 to 0-1 million years ago southeastward.{{sfn|Vlastelic|Dosso|Guillou|Bougault|1998|p=778,779}} Three [[fracture zone]]s, the Heezen, Tharp and Hollister fracture zones, extend northwestward across the seafloor northeast of the Hollister Ridge;{{sfn|Vlastelic|Dosso|Guillou|Bougault|1998|p=779}} at least the first two are considered to be part of the [[Eltanin fracture zone]].{{sfn|Vlastélic|Dosso|2005|p=11}} A [[Escarpment|scarp]] lies south of the Hollister Ridge,{{sfn|Géli|Aslanian|Olivet|Vlastelic|1998|p=35}} and even farther south lies the Udintsev fracture zone.{{sfn|Vlastélic|Dosso|2005|p=2}} The Pacific-Antarctic Ridge close to the Hollister Ridge is the site of an isolated [[geoid]] anomaly which has been interpreted as a product of [[magma]]tic [[upwelling]].{{sfn|Talandier|Okal|1996|p=1533}}

Rocks sampled from the Hollister Ridge have yielded [[basalt]]s,{{sfn|Vlastelic|Dosso|Guillou|Bougault|1998|p=779}} [[alkali basalt]]s, [[hawaiite]]s, [[picrite]]s and [[tholeiite]]s{{sfn|Vlastelic|Dosso|Guillou|Bougault|1998|p=780}} as well as [[granite]]s, which are most likely [[dropstone]]s transported to the ridge by [[iceberg]]s. The basalts range from [[aphyric]] to [[porphyric]] and contain [[phenocryst]]s of [[olivine]] and [[plagioclase]].{{sfn|Vlastelic|Dosso|Guillou|Bougault|1998|p=779}} 

Several mechanisms have been proposed to explain its origin:{{sfn|Vlastelic|Dosso|Guillou|Bougault|1998|p=777}}
* The ridge may be the present-day location of the [[Louisville hotspot]].{{sfn|Okal|Langenhorst|2000|p=186}}{{sfn|Vlastelic|Dosso|Guillou|Bougault|1998|p=777}} Petrological differences between the volcanoes formed by this hotspot and the Hollister Ridge make this hypothesis problematic,{{sfn|Vlastelic|Dosso|Guillou|Bougault|1998|p=792}}{{sfn|Okal|Langenhorst|2000|p=186}} as are misfits between the reconstructed path of the Louisville hotspot and the position of the Hollister Ridge.{{sfn|Géli|Aslanian|Olivet|Vlastelic|1998|p=32}} Even later plate reconstructions have endorsed this model of origin.<ref name="MorganMorgan2007" /> 
* A "mini-[[hotspot (geology)|hotspot]]", which however is not consistent with the geometry of the ridge (which is at an angle to the motion of the [[Pacific Plate]]).{{sfn|Géli|Aslanian|Olivet|Vlastelic|1998|p=35}} Such a mini-hotspot may be a branch of the Louisville hotspot.{{sfn|Vlastélic|Dosso|2005|p=10}}
* [[Asthenosphere]] may be flowing from the Louisville hotspot to the Pacific-Antarctic Ridge.{{sfn|Vlastelic|Dosso|Guillou|Bougault|1998|p=777}} Seamounts and aseismic ridges have been observed in other regions of the world where such flow is expected to occur.{{sfn|Vlastélic|Dosso|2005|p=2}}
* [[Lineament]]s in the [[crust (geology)|crust]] allowed the ascent of [[magma]] from the [[mantle (geology)|mantle]].{{sfn|Vlastelic|Dosso|Guillou|Bougault|1998|p=791}} Such lineaments may be produced by tectonic stresses related to crustal spreading; this theory is supported by the geometry of the Hollister Ridge and the ages of its components. There may be some influence by the Louisville hotspot.{{sfn|Géli|Aslanian|Olivet|Vlastelic|1998|p=37}} [[Pliocene]] changes in the plate motion patterns of the region may have generated the lineaments.<ref name="Peive2007" />
* One variation of the "lineament" theory posits that the ridge at first was built by magma ascending through crustal weaknesses; later material from the Louisville hotspot flowed south towards the Hollister Ridge and increasingly interacted with the lineament, thus influencing the composition of the ridge rocks.{{sfn|Vlastélic|Dosso|2005|p=12}} A change in [[lithospheric]] thickness across the Eltanin fracture zone would divert the mantle flow from the Louisville hotspot southward.{{sfn|Castillo|Natland|Niu|Lonsdale|1998|p=121}}

== Eruptive history ==

[[Argon-argon dating]] has yielded ages ranging from a mean age of 2.531 ± 0.036 million years ago for the western ridge{{sfn|Vlastelic|Dosso|Guillou|Bougault|1998|p=783}} over 0.487 ± 0.03 million years ago and 0.343 ± 0.008 million years ago for the eastern ridge to 91,000 ± 12,000 and 0 years ago for the central ridge. This implies that volcanism is still active{{sfn|Vlastelic|Dosso|Guillou|Bougault|1998|p=781}} at the central ridge, which is also the shallowest sector of the Hollister Ridge.{{sfn|Vlastelic|Dosso|Guillou|Bougault|1998|p=783}}

There is evidence of historical eruptions at the Hollister Ridge.{{sfn|Géli|Aslanian|Olivet|Vlastelic|1998|p=32}} Between 10 March 1991 and 12 June 1992 a strong [[acoustic swarm]] was recorded in the southern [[Pacific Ocean]] from several stations in [[French Polynesia]]{{sfn|Talandier|Okal|1996|p=1530}} and its source identified with a segment of the Hollister Ridge.{{sfn|Talandier|Okal|1996|p=1532}} [[Environmental noise|Anthropogenic]] and biological origins were considered unlikely sources for the swarm,{{sfn|Talandier|Okal|1996|p=1536}} and it is thus interpreted to be a volcanic swarm.<ref name="GVP" /> The acoustic swarm may have resulted from the interaction between seawater and a subaqueous [[lava lake]];{{sfn|Talandier|Okal|1996|p=1542}} the acoustic patterns are not consistent with a simple [[explosive eruption]].<ref name="GVP" />

